IOM’s ethical recruitment programming sustains and promotes a multi-stakeholder approach to advance the protection of migrant workers. This approach aims to ensure that programming is inclusive and responds to the needs of governments and the private sector, while empowering and promoting the voices of migrant workers and their representatives in , including trade unions. The multi-stakeholder approach also promotes collaboration and partnership with international organizations, including United Nations agencies.      
Ethical recruitment means hiring workers lawfully, consistent with international standards and principles, in a fair and transparent manner that respects and protects their rights. Ethical recruitment is in line with the United Nations Guiding Principles on Business and Human Rights, international standards on ethical recruitment and responsible business conduct, as well as related conventions. 
The International Recruitment Integrity System (IRIS) Standard is a set of global principles that define ethical recruitment. It is based on international labour and human rights instruments and was developed through extensive multi-stakeholder consultations. The IRIS Standard sets out what ethical recruitment means in practice and how labour recruiters can demonstrate compliance. 
The seven core IRIS principles are: 
  1. Respect for laws, fundamental principles and rights at work; 
  2. Respect for ethical and professional conduct; 
  3. Prohibition of recruitment fees to jobseekers; 
  4. Respect for freedom of movement; 
  5. Respect for transparency of terms and conditions of employment; 
  6. Respect for confidentiality and data protection; 
  7. Respect for access to remedy.

Ethical recruitment contributes directly to target 10.7 of the Sustainable Development Goals, which calls for orderly, safe, regular and responsible migration. It reinforces efforts to achieve targets 8.5 and 8.7 of the Sustainable Development Goals on productive employment, decent work for all and the eradication of forced labour, modern slavery and human trafficking and protection of human and labour rights. Objective 6 of the [Global Compact for Safe, Orderly and Regular Migration](https://www.iom.int/global-compact-migration "Global compact for safe, orderly and regular migration") outlines actions for Member States to facilitate fair and ethical recruitment and safeguard conditions that ensure decent work.     
In recognition of the vital role the private sector plays in enhancing respect for the rights of migrant workers, and in alignment with the United Nations “Protect, Respect and Remedy” Framework, ethical recruitment is a core component of IOM’s programmatic approach to migration, business and human rights. This approach is centered on bridging the gaps between established international norms, corporate aspirations and joint operational actions to protect and respect human rights and the environment in the private sector. 
IOM’s migration, business and human rights and ethical recruitment programming establishes partnerships with the private sector to uphold the rights of migrant workers and protect them throughout their migration journeys. IOM advocates strengthened government regulations for employers and recruiters in the private sector. 
The work conducted by IOM on ethical recruitment bolsters business and human rights initiatives and partnerships. This work includes guidance, resources and interventions which:
  * Strengthen and address gaps in corporate and supply chain policies; 
  * Enhance due diligence and social compliance to better identify and address risks that migrant workers face in supply chains;

## SPOTLIGHT ON SSI BENEFITS FOR NONCITIZENS -- 2025 Edition
#### UNDER WHAT CIRCUMSTANCES MAY A NONCITIZEN BE ELIGIBLE FOR SSI?
A noncitizen (also called an “alien” for immigration purposes) may be eligible for SSI if he or she meets the requirements of the laws for noncitizens that went into effect on August 22, 1996. In general, beginning August 22, 1996, most noncitizens must meet two requirements to be potentially eligible for SSI:
be in a category; and meet a condition that allows qualified aliens to get SSI. 
A noncitizen must also meet all of the other rules for , including the limits on and , etc.   
There are 7 categories of qualified aliens. You are a qualified alien if the Department of Homeland Security (DHS) says you are in one of these categories:
  1. Lawfully Admitted for Permanent Residence (LAPR) in the U.S., which includes"Amerasian immigrant" as defined in P.L. 100-202, with a class of admission AM-1 through AM-8;
  2. Granted conditional entry under Section 203(a)(7) of the Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) as in effect before April 1, 1980;
  3. Paroled into the U.S. under Section 212(d)(5) of the INA for a period of at least one year;
  4. Refugee admitted to the U.S. under Section 207 of the INA;
  5. Granted asylum under Section 208 of the INA;
  6. Deportation is being withheld under Section 243(h) of the INA, as in effect before April 1, 1997; or removal is being withheld under Section 241(b)(3) of the INA;
  7. A "Cuban or Haitian entrant" as defined in Section 501(e) of the Refugee Education Assistance Act of 1980 or in a status that is to be treated as a "Cuban/ Haitian entrant" for SSI purposes.

